@alexpearce I suspect this problem is from the `ProxyDataDescriptor._process_set_value` level of the stack trace in #1325 
When assigning an object to an attribute of a `GangaObject` type class Ganga will immediately attempt to understand the object being assigned to a member variable in the context of the current namespace. This would allow it to use things such as types defined at runtime by the user.
This is really a fiddly area of the code as the objects have to be instantiated in the correct order.

The actual _bug_ here is that Ganga seems to be wasting CPU by parsing all possible objects in the namespace prior to the attribute assignment. (which in Ganga terms creates a new instance of the object upon assignment and is therefore closer to a deep copy which is needed for thread-safe internal behavior).
That being said I don't know another way of walking up/down an objects inheritance path to determine if the proxy layer has added/removed the appropriate proxies to any children to build up the Ganga public/private model within Python. I can semi-construct some solutions but these quickly become complex pieces of code.

