Looks like more in the category of "stack unwinding on pthread exit causes Python operations to be performed without the GIL held". Unfortunately, I can't think of a good general-purpose solution here. Ideally the unwinding would be performed with the GIL held, but Python (being written in C) has no concept of unwinding at all. Checking for `Py_IsInitialized` in the py::object destructor like we did for py::gil_scoped_acquire seems overkill, and would probably impact performance adversely.

If you don't mind being flagrantly Linux-specific, you could rewrite your thread function like so:
```
auto gil = std::make_unique<py::gil_scoped_acquire>();
py::object func = m.attr("func");
py::tuple args = py::make_tuple(this);
try {
    // no pybind object allocations allowed in here, not even temporaries
    PyObject_Call(func.ptr(), args.ptr(), nullptr);
} catch (abi::__forced_unwind&) {
    // forced stack unwinding at thread exit --
    // if Python is shutting down, don't clean up Python state
    if (!Py_IsInitialized()) {
        args.release();
        func.release();
        gil.release();
    }
    throw;     // rethrow is very important!
}
```

@peterbarker The lack of escape char is a limitation, but it just means the JSON has to be last. Not so much an issue for this PR but for #394 order will matter. e.g. `link add tcp:127.0.0.1:14550:{"label":"foo"}` will work but `link add tcp:127.0.0.1:{"label":"foo"}:14550` will not.

 __TL:DR__ everything after the first `:{` is assumed to be JSON _if_ the final char is `}`. 

